05816nam a22008055i 9780231542982DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016010615  a(OCoLC)979683333  a97802315429827 a10.7312/roge178562doi  a(DE-B1597)478141  a(OCoLC)960281440  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPQ6073.M6bR636 2016 4aPQ6073.M6bR636 2017 7aLIT0040502bisacsh04a860.91122231 aRogers, Gayle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIncomparable Empires :bModernism and the Translation of Spanish and American Literature /cGayle Rogers. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aModernist Latitudes00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Modernism, Translation, and the Fields of Literary History -- tI. American Modernism’s Hispanists -- t1. “Splintered Staves”: Pound, Comparative Literature, and the Translation of Spanish Literary History -- t2. Restaging the Disaster: Dos Passos, Empire, and Literature After the Spanish-American War -- tII. Spain’s American Translations -- t3. Jiménez, Modernism/o, and the Languages of Comparative Modernist Studies -- t4. Unamuno, Nativism, and the Politics of the Vernacular; or, On the Authenticity of Translation -- tIII. New Genealogies -- t5. Negro and Negro: Translating American Blackness in the Shadows of the Spanish Empire -- t6. “Spanish Is a Language Tu”: Hemingway’s Cubist Spanglish and Its Legacies -- tConclusion: Worlds Between Languages— The Spanglish Quixote -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Spanish-American War of 1898 seems to mark a turning point in both geopolitical and literary histories. The victorious American empire ascended and began its cultural domination of the globe in the twentieth century, while the once-mighty Spanish empire declined and became a minor state in the world republic of letters. But what if this narrative relies on several faulty assumptions, and what if key modernist figures in both America and Spain radically rewrote these histories at a foundational moment of modern literary studies?Following networks of American and Spanish writers, translators, and movements, Gayle Rogers uncovers the arguments that forged the politics and aesthetics of modernism. He revisits the role of empire—from its institutions to its cognitive effects—in shaping a nation's literature and culture. Ranging from universities to comparative practices, from Ezra Pound's failed ambitions as a Hispanist to Juan Ramón Jiménez's multilingual maps of modernismo, Rogers illuminates modernists' profound engagements with the formative dynamics of exceptionalist American and Spanish literary studies. He reads the provocative, often counterintuitive arguments of John Dos Passos, who held that "American literature" could only flourish if the expanding U.S. empire collapsed like Spain's did. And he also details both a controversial theorization of a Harlem–Havana–Madrid nexus for black modernist writing and Ernest Hemingway's unorthodox development of a version of cubist Spanglish in For Whom the Bell Tolls. Bringing together revisionary literary historiography and rich textual analyses, Rogers offers a striking account of why foreign literatures mattered so much to two dramatically changing countries at a pivotal moment in history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican literaturexTranslationsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Literature)zSpain. 0aModernism (Literature)zUnited States. 0aSpanish literaturexTranslati